                  "marks": [
                    {
                      "type": "code"
                    }
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "text": " columns are indexed. This will improve the performance of the DELETE operation by allowing SQL Server to quickly locate the records to be deleted."
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "listItem",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "text": "Transaction Log",
                  "marks": [
                    {
                      "type": "strong"
                    }
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "text": ": Deleting records can generate a significant amount of transaction log activity, especially if the table contains a large number of records. Consider using batch deletes if the dataset is large to manage log growth and reduce locking."
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "listItem",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "text": "Locking and Blocking",
                  "marks": [
                    {
                      "type": "strong"
                    }
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "text": ": The DELETE operation will acquire locks on the rows being deleted, which could lead to blocking if other transactions are trying to access the same data. Monitor and manage concurrency to minimize impact."
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
